{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486745"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:43:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:43:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"167"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/167"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.24,0.12,0.57,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"167"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90833"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/167"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"167"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74896"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"221"},{"type":"tags","id":"316"},{"type":"tags","id":"1197"},{"type":"tags","id":"2571"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5686"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31131"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42975"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44746"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90833"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a three-month history of bilateral wrist and knee pain associated with early morning stiffness. She also reports unintentional weight loss of approximately 5 kg and intermittent haemoptysis over the past month. She has a medical history of postpartum deep venous thrombosis treated with three months of anticoagulation. She takes no regular medications. She is an active smoker with a 30 pack-year smoking history and drinks two glasses of wine per day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, there is tenderness over both wrists and knees and she is noted to have convex nail beds. There is also nicotine staining of the right second and third digits. On auscultation of the chest, there is decreased air entry bilaterally and a widespread expiratory wheeze.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation to request next?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Uric acid","Rheumatoid factor and anti-citrullinated peptide antibodies","Anti-double-stranded (ds)DNA antibodies","Computed tomography of the chest","Pulmonary function tests"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHypertrophic pulmonary osteoarthropathy (HPOA) presents with the triad of digital clubbing, periostitis, and painful arthropathy (most commonly large joints of lower limbs). Most cases of secondary HPOA are related to underlying lung cancer, particularly adenocarcinoma. The patient is at risk for lung cancer due to cigarette smoking and possible underlying chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). The history of unintentional weight loss and haemoptysis also supports this diagnosis. Given the high pre-test probability, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomputed tomography of the chest \u003C/strong\u003Eshould be the next step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Epulmonary function tests\u003C/strong\u003E may confirm the diagnosis of COPD, this is not the priority as the presence of HPOA, unintentional weight loss, and haemoptysis suggest a more sinister diagnosis. However, patients planned for surgical resection of lung cancer require pulmonary function tests for pre-operative assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHPOA may resemble rheumatoid arthritis (RA), given the presentation with symmetric polyarthritis however nail clubbing is not seen in RA. Haemoptysis is also not seen in RA unless complicated by diffuse alveolar hemorrhage which is rare. \u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid factor and anti-citrullinated peptide antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E may be present in RA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-dsDNA antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E may be present in systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE). While this is plausible given its versatile manifestations including symmetrical polyarthritis, weight loss and organ involvement, this is not the most likely diagnosis. Given the risk factors for lung cancer and typical symptoms, this should be looked at first. Most cases of SLE present between 15-54 years of age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGouty arthritis may develop as a result of \u003Cstrong\u003Ehyperuricaemia\u003C/strong\u003E. This diagnosis is less likely as lower-extremity involvement (particularly podagra, the first metatarsophalangeal joint) is more common in gout. A monoarticular presentation is also more common.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hypertrophic pulmonary osteoarthropathy (HPOA)  presents with the triad of digital clubbing, periostitis, and painful arthropathy.","Most cases of secondary HPOA are due to lung cancer, particularly adenocarcinoma."],"references":["Shamji FM, Beauchamp G, Maziak DE, Cooper J. Paraneoplastic Syndromes in Lung Cancers: Manifestations of Ectopic Endocrinological Syndromes and Neurologic Syndromes. Thorac Surg Clin. 2021;31(4):519\u201337. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34696864/","Fanouriakis A, Tziolos N, Bertsias G, Boumpas DT. Update \u03bfn the diagnosis and management of systemic lupus erythematosus. Ann Rheum Dis. 2021;80(1):14-25. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33051219/","Shinzato A, Kinjo T, Miyagi T, Yamazato S, Kaneku K, Nishiyama M, et al. Hypertrophic pulmonary osteoarthropathy due to lung cancer: A case report and literature review. Clin Case Rep. 2020;8(12):3509\u201313. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7752478/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74896"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"167"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74896","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74896"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T16:46:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T16:46:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"167"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90833"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id